      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 4-year-old child is brought to the clinic by their mother due to pain in the right hip and difficulty walking. Physical examination reveals no significant external abnormalities. An X-ray of the hip is performed, showing increased bone density and abnormal bone structure. Based on the clinical presentation and the radiographic findings, what is the most likely diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/26/picture7_62YQqVU.jpg\" style=\"height:268px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6774883",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33032,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D. Both A and C </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The diagnosis based on the history of pain in the right hip and difficulty in walking in a child along with X-ray hip findings of <strong>sclerosis &amp; thickening of the bones appearing like a marble</strong> is suggestive of <strong>Osteopetrosis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It is also known as <strong>Marble bone disease.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">X ray spine reveals characteristic Rugger-jersey appearance.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>A: Osteopetrosis:</strong> This option is <strong>correct </strong>as osteopetrosis presents with increased bone density, which can lead to symptoms like pain and movement difficulties.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>B: Paget&rsquo;s disease:</strong> Paget&#39;s disease typically <strong>affects older adults </strong>and is characterized by <strong>abnormal bone remodelling</strong>, leading to enlarged and misshapen bones. It is less likely to be the cause of symptoms in a 4-year-old.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C: Marble bone disease:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This is another name for osteopetrosis, making this option also <strong>correct</strong>. The condition is named for the marble-like appearance of bones on an X-ray due to their increased density.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Osteopetrosis</strong>, also known as <strong>Marble Bone Disease</strong>, is characterized by <strong>increased bone density </strong>due to a <strong>defect in osteoclast-mediated bone resorption</strong>. This <strong>leads to bones </strong>that are <strong>denser but more brittle</strong>, which can <strong>cause pain </strong>and <strong>difficulty in movement</strong>, such as <strong>walking</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">- Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No-3375-3376.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
